-- SE Asia Stocks -Malaysia, Singapore post worst weekly losses since March
-- By Viparat Jantraprap
-- Fri Aug 08, 2014 06:37AM EDT
-- None



BANGKOK, Aug 8 (Reuters) - Stocks in Malaysia and Singapore suffered their worst weekly losses in five months on Friday amid rising global risk aversion and a fall in regional currencies after U.S. President Barack Obama's authorisation of air strikes in Iraq. [ID:nL4N0QE3BS]

Malaysia's main index <.KLSE> dropped 1.5 percent to the lowest close since March 26, sliding 1.3 percent on the week. Foreign investors were net sellers of shares worth 122 million ringgit ($38 million) on Friday, stock exchange data showed. Singapore's Straits Times Index <.FTSTI> was down 0.8 percent on the day and 1.7 percent on the week. Shares of realtor UOL Group Ltd <UTOS.SI> slipped 1.4 percent after the company said its second-quarter net profit fell by more than half. [ID:nL4N0QE4OK] Other equities markets in Southeast Asia had a mixed weekly performance, with Indonesia <.JKSE> and the Philippines <.PSI> little changed while Vietnam <.VNI> rose 1.9 percent, the region's best performer. Thai stocks <.SETI> climbed 1.3 percent on the week, recouping some of the 2.8 percent losses a week earlier. The Thai stock market will be closed on Monday and Tuesday for a public holiday.